<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1437,402,1867]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">
<emphasis box="[199,338,727,750]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Description.</emphasis>
General body shape and colour: elongated but stout body, mottled brown and black or dirty greenish (
<figureCitation box="[266,352,762,787]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="29.[151,250,1071,1093]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1049]" captionTargetId="figure@29.[151,1436,193,1050]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURE 18. Male Apteroscirtus cristatus n. sp., Mazumbai forest reserve in the West Usambara Mountains. Arrows point to keels of abdominal tergites which are conspicuous in this species, but hardly discernible in A. planidorsatus n. sp. from the Uluguru Mountains and thus a good character distinguishing these two Tanzanian species." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/248338/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[369,400,763,787]" captionStart="FIGURE 19" captionStartId="30.[151,250,995,1017]" captionTargetBox="[225,1401,176,974]" captionTargetId="figure@30.[192,1402,168,974]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 19. Male Apteroscirtus cristatus n. sp., habitus, semilateral view; Mazumbai forest reserve." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/248339/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">19</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis box="[425,684,762,787]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Head and antennae.—</emphasis>
Antennae more than twice the body length, about 
<quantity box="[1280,1367,762,787]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="4.0" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" unit="cm" value="4.5" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="4.0">4–5 cm</quantity>
long. Fastigium verticis flat, constricted at height of eyes and widening towards height of antennae (
<figureCitation box="[1217,1300,798,823]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="30.[151,250,1983,2005]" captionTargetBox="[210,1378,1057,1961]" captionTargetId="figure@30.[210,1378,1057,1962]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 20. Morphological details of male Apteroscirtus species. A, B. Fastigium verticis, A. cristatus n. sp. (A) and A. planidorsatus n. sp. (B). C, D. Male abdominal apex, A. cristatus (C) and A. planidorsatus (D)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/248340/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">
Fig. 
<number box="[1270,1300,799,823]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" value="20.0">20</number>
</figureCitation>
A); abruptly forming acute angle to face, meeting fastigium of frons in a shallow horizontal line. 
<emphasis box="[1212,1325,834,859]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Thorax.—</emphasis>
Pronotum constricted at first sulcus; disk of pronotum flat and smooth with faint median carina. Lateral lobes of pronotum smooth, brown-black marked bordering disk of pronotum. Disk of meso- and metazona of pronotum almost triangular, with slightly undulating posterior margin of pronotum. Sulcus dividing meso- and metazona deep, running almost to lower margin of pronotal lobes. Tegmina tiny rounded lobes, hardly protruding from posterior margin of pronotum. 
<emphasis box="[389,474,1015,1038]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Legs.—</emphasis>
Legs long and slender, base of hind femur stout. 
<collectingCountry box="[1017,1073,1014,1039]" name="India" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Hind</collectingCountry>
femora surpassing apex of body about 
<number box="[221,256,1050,1075]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" value="1.5">1.5</number>
times of their length, hind tibiae as long as femora. Tympana of fore tibiae oval and open on both sides. All femora unarmed. Fore and mid tibiae unarmed except for few spines at posterior outer side. 
<collectingCountry box="[1251,1307,1086,1111]" name="India" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Hind</collectingCountry>
tibiae with double-row of numerous stout spines along dorsal side, and few spines at posterior part on inner sides of hind tibiae. 
<emphasis box="[229,367,1158,1183]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Abdomen.—</emphasis>
Abdominal tergites medially with conspicuous keels (
<figureCitation box="[981,1066,1158,1183]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="29.[151,250,1071,1093]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1049]" captionTargetId="figure@29.[151,1436,193,1050]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURE 18. Male Apteroscirtus cristatus n. sp., Mazumbai forest reserve in the West Usambara Mountains. Arrows point to keels of abdominal tergites which are conspicuous in this species, but hardly discernible in A. planidorsatus n. sp. from the Uluguru Mountains and thus a good character distinguishing these two Tanzanian species." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/248338/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">
Fig. 
<number box="[1036,1066,1159,1183]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" value="18.0">18</number>
</figureCitation>
), elongating posterior margin of tergites. Lateral on abdomen dark brown to black fascia. Cerci stout and of light colour, slightly curved inwardly (
<figureCitation box="[159,245,1230,1255]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="30.[151,250,1983,2005]" captionTargetBox="[210,1378,1057,1961]" captionTargetId="figure@30.[210,1378,1057,1962]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 20. Morphological details of male Apteroscirtus species. A, B. Fastigium verticis, A. cristatus n. sp. (A) and A. planidorsatus n. sp. (B). C, D. Male abdominal apex, A. cristatus (C) and A. planidorsatus (D)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/248340/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">
Fig. 
<number box="[214,245,1231,1255]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" value="20.0">20</number>
</figureCitation>
C). Subgenital plate typical for 
<taxonomicName box="[610,760,1231,1254]" class="Insecta" family="Phaneropteridae" genus="Apteroscirtus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[610,760,1231,1254]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Apteroscirtus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, elongate and acute forked at its posterior end (
<figureCitation box="[1318,1404,1230,1255]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="30.[151,250,1983,2005]" captionTargetBox="[210,1378,1057,1961]" captionTargetId="figure@30.[210,1378,1057,1962]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 20. Morphological details of male Apteroscirtus species. A, B. Fastigium verticis, A. cristatus n. sp. (A) and A. planidorsatus n. sp. (B). C, D. Male abdominal apex, A. cristatus (C) and A. planidorsatus (D)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/248340/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">
Fig. 
<number box="[1373,1404,1231,1255]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" value="20.0">20</number>
</figureCitation>
C). Styli minute little dots.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1437,402,1867]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">
Female.—Larger than male. No signs of tegmina, thus completely apterous. 
<collectingCountry box="[1066,1122,1302,1327]" name="India" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Hind</collectingCountry>
femora very stout and long but only surpassing body about half of their total length. Ovipositor stout and slightly up-curved at posterior part (
<figureCitation box="[159,241,1374,1399]" captionStart="FIGURE 21" captionStartId="31.[151,250,1995,2017]" captionTargetBox="[172,1432,977,1942]" captionTargetId="figure@31.[154,1433,977,1972]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="FIGURE 21. Ovipositors of Apteroscirtus species. A. A. cristatus n. sp. B. A. planidorsatus n. sp." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/248341/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">
Fig. 
<number box="[212,241,1375,1399]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" value="21.0">21</number>
</figureCitation>
A). Subgenital plate broad with straight posterior margin (
<figureCitation box="[890,973,1374,1399]" captionStart="FIGURE 22" captionStartId="32.[151,250,731,753]" captionTargetBox="[150,1434,207,691]" captionTargetId="figure@32.[149,1434,207,691]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="FIGURE 22. Subgenital plates of female Apteroscirtus species. A. A. cristatus n. sp. B. A. planidorsatus n. sp." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/248342/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">
Fig. 
<number box="[943,973,1375,1399]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" value="22.0">22</number>
</figureCitation>
A).
</paragraph>
